---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Community Mobilization Overview" description="What is community mobilization and how does the chapter journey work?">

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">Community Mobilization Overview</span>
      <h1>An approach, not a program.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Community mobilization is the process of identifying and bringing together community stakeholders to raise awareness, assist in delivery of services, and strengthen self-reliance. Here is how it works.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <div class="prose">

        <h2>What it is</h2>
        <p>
          Community mobilization is not a campaign. It is not a series of events. It is an orientation — a way of working that centers community voice, builds on existing assets, and creates the conditions for communities to lead their own resilience.
        </p>
        <p>
          It works by asking different questions. Not "what does this community need?" but "what does this community already have?" Not "how do we help?" but "how do we connect people to each other and to what they already hold?"
        </p>

        <h2>The foundation: Asset-Based Community Development</h2>
        <p>
          The organizing philosophy of community mobilization is ABCD — Asset-Based Community Development. Every community has assets: people, organizations, institutions, places, networks, and cultural knowledge. Those assets are often invisible to outsiders and underused even by the community itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          Community mobilization starts by finding and mapping those assets — not as a data collection exercise, but as a relational process of building trust and discovering what is already present and possible.
        </p>

        <h2>The chapter journey</h2>
        <p>
          The chapter journey is the path a Red Cross chapter walks as it deepens community mobilization work. It is not linear. It is recursive — a cycle that a chapter returns to, deepens, and begins again as teams change, priorities shift, and communities evolve.
        </p>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PHASES -->
  <section class="section" style="background: var(--surf-2);">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">The six phases</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom: 2.5rem;">The journey, phase by phase</h2>
      <div class="grid-2">
        {[
          {
            num: '01', phase: 'Preconditions', color: '#552F1C',
            desc: 'Before anything else, the team builds the internal conditions for this work — honest self-reflection, shared values, and genuine relationships.',
            skills: ['Self-Discovery', 'Trust-Building Conversations', 'Who Speaks Matters'],
          },
          {
            num: '02', phase: 'Internal Asset Mapping', color: '#557A35',
            desc: 'The chapter identifies and maps what the community already has — people, organizations, places, networks, and cultural knowledge.',
            skills: ['Linking People and Possibilities', 'Data-Informed Learning'],
          },
          {
            num: '03', phase: 'Priority Area Selection', color: '#CA9B33',
            desc: 'Using data and community voice, the chapter identifies a specific priority area where it can have meaningful, sustained impact.',
            skills: ['Data-Informed Learning', 'Purposeful Meetings'],
          },
          {
            num: '04', phase: 'Community Discovery', color: '#0097B2',
            desc: 'Listening before planning. The chapter builds relationships with community stakeholders and hears directly from those most affected.',
            skills: ['Trust-Building Conversations', 'Purposeful Meetings', 'Decision-Making Without Authority'],
          },
          {
            num: '05', phase: 'Planning & Execution', color: '#7F4D94',
            desc: 'With a clear picture of assets and priorities, the chapter designs and launches a layered strategy — coordinated across individual, community, organizational, and systems levels.',
            skills: ['Strategic Prioritization', 'Building Across Levels', 'Decision-Making Without Authority'],
          },
          {
            num: '06', phase: 'Sustaining & Transferring', color: '#00BE88',
            desc: 'The work is intentionally handed back to community leadership. The chapter shifts from leading to supporting — and begins the cycle again.',
            skills: ['Community Program Support'],
          },
        ].map(p => (
          <div class="card" style="border-top: 4px solid transparent;" data-phase={p.phase}>
            <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
              <span style={`font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: ${p.color};`}>{p.num}</span>
              <h3 style={`color: ${p.color}; font-size: 1.125rem;`}>{p.phase}</h3>
            </div>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">{p.desc}</p>
            <div>
              <div style="font-size: 0.7rem; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--ink-3); margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Key Skills</div>
              <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.375rem;">
                {p.skills.map(s => (
                  <span style="font-size: 0.8rem; background: var(--surf-2); padding: 3px 8px; border-radius: 4px; color: var(--ink-2);">{s}</span>
                ))}
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <div style="margin-top: 2rem; padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--white); border-radius: var(--r-lg); border: 1px solid var(--rule);">
        <p style="color: var(--ink-2); font-style: italic; margin: 0; max-width: none;">
          ↻ <strong style="font-style: normal;">This process is recursive and reflective.</strong> After Planning & Execution, a chapter reflects, learns from feedback, and returns — sometimes to Preconditions with a new team, sometimes to Community Discovery with a new priority. Return to any phase at any point in the journey.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <div class="prose">

        <h2>Why this approach works</h2>
        <p>
          Programs that start with needs assessments tend to reinforce a deficit view of communities — seeing people for what they lack, not what they bring. Programs that start with asset mapping tend to build something different: genuine partnership, durable trust, and solutions that actually fit the community because the community helped design them.
        </p>
        <p>
          Community mobilization also works because it is honest about power. Who gets to define the problem? Who gets to decide what counts as a solution? Who is at the table — and whose voice carries weight when it gets there? The skills in this hub take those questions seriously and provide tools for navigating them.
        </p>

        <h2>The role of the Executive Director</h2>
        <p>
          The Executive Director is not the community mobilizer. The ED is the person who creates the conditions for mobilization to happen — by building a team with the right skills, creating authentic partnerships, managing up and across organizational structures, and making decisions without always having formal authority to make them.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is a genuinely difficult role. The 10 skills in this hub are the tools for doing it well.
        </p>

      </div>

      <div style="margin-top: 3rem; display: flex; gap: 0.75rem;">
        <a href="/skills" class="btn btn-primary">Explore the 10 skills</a>
        <a href="/resources" class="btn btn-outline">See resources</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
